mpted to teach Cerwonka, then new to the discipline, the basic tools and subtle intuition needed for anthropological fieldwork. The result is a strikingly original dissection of the processual ethics and politics of method in ethnography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aCerwonka, Allaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalkki, Liisa H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMalkki, Liisa H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalkki, Liisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226100289423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226100289.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles